In reality, I know but of one solid Objection to absolute Monarchy.
The only Defect of this excellent Constitution seems to be the Difficulty of finding any Man adequate to the Office of an absolute Monarch: For this indispensably requires three Qualities very difficult, as this appears from History, to be found in princely Natures: First a sufficient Quantity of Moderation in the Prince, to be contented with all the Power which is possible for the Prince to have.
2dly, Enough of Wisdom to know the Prince own Happiness.
And, 3dly, Goodness sufficient to support the Happiness of others, when not only compatible with, but instrumental to the Prince own.
Now if an absolute Monarch with all these great and rare Qualifications should be allowed capable of conferring the greatest Good on Society, it must be surely granted, on the contrary, that absolute Power vested in the Hands of one who is deficient in them all, is likely to be attended with no less a Degree of Evil.
In short our own Religion furnishes our with adequate Ideas of the Blessing, as well as Curse which may attend absolute Power.
